**Solution 1: [Accepted]388ms**
This Solution is a variation of Subset Sum, but we want only unique Subset. Therefore, to keep track of that, I use a set of vector type and store them in sorted only. *[Reason for storing  them in sorted only, is beacuse if I have a target=7, and Array=[2,3,2,1,2,2,1] and let's say we got two subset [1,2,2,2] && [2,1,2,2] which is equal to our target, but in this case they are not unique subset. {Unique is when we have the frequencies of any value in a subset , is different from another subset.} But, in this case Frequencies of every value in both subset are same. Therefore, they must be treated as a single subset not two different subset].*  So, if I find a duplicate one, I will not going to push it into  my answer.
Below, is the Code which is just a subset Sum variaton.
```
class Solution {
public:
    set<vector<int>> s;
    vector<vector<int>> combinationSum2(vector<int>& candidates, int target) {
        int n=candidates.size();
        vector<vector<int>> ans;
        vector<int> temp;

        PrintSubset(candidates,n,target,ans, temp);
        return ans;
    }
    void PrintSubset(vector<int>&candidates,int n, int target,vector<vector<int>> &ans,vector<int>temp)
    {
        if(target==0)
        {
            sort(temp.begin(),temp.end());
            if(s.find(temp)==s.end())
            {
                ans.push_back(temp);
                s.insert(temp);
            }
            return;
        }
        if(n==0)
            return;
        if(target<candidates[n-1])
            PrintSubset(candidates,n-1,target,ans,temp);
        else
        {
            temp.push_back(candidates[n-1]);
            PrintSubset(candidates, n-1, target-candidates[n-1],ans,temp);
            temp.pop_back();
            PrintSubset(candidates, n-1, target, ans, temp);
        }
    }
};
```
Now, in above Code we are taking extra space and we always sorting it to so that we can keep only unique subsets in our final answer.
We can modify the above solution, by sorting the candidates at first. Now the duplicates ones are adjacent to each other and we can easily skip that ones which are Duplicates.

**Solution #2: [Accepted] 8ms**
Sort the candidates vector. And Now, when you have encounter a duplicate value, skip that value, because they may form same subset as previous one has formed. So, run a while loop and skip until you find a unique value.
Now, we don't need extra space and we don't have to sort again and again. Just a little bit of change, and everything is same as above code.

```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<vector<int>> combinationSum2(vector<int>& candidates, int target) {
        int n=candidates.size();
        sort(candidates.begin(),candidates.end());
        vector<vector<int>> ans;
        vector<int> temp;
        PrintSubset(candidates,0,n,target,ans, temp);
        return ans;
    }
    void PrintSubset(vector<int>&C,int index,int n, int target,vector<vector<int>> &ans,vector<int>&temp)
    {
        if(target==0)
        {
            ans.push_back(temp);
            return;
        }
        if(index>=n)
            return;
        if(target<0)
            return ;
        temp.push_back(C[index]);
        PrintSubset(C,index+1,n,target-C[index],ans,temp);
        while(index<(n-1) && C[index]==C[index+1])
            index++;
        temp.pop_back();
        PrintSubset(C,index+1,n,target,ans,temp);
    }
};
```
*And yes, this Q's can also be solved using Backtracking. Many users has posted brilliant backtracking solutions, you can check that also.*

