solutions.content:
Here, we can't perform normal backtracking as it would lead to 2^n cases(where n<=100 given). So we tweak the code a bit so that we don't have to produce the same combinations again and again.

Steps used:
-> After sorting the initial array, follow the below steps
-> add the curr element from target and backtrack for the leftover part of array.
-> don't add the curr element from the target and backtrack for the leftover part of the array.
-> if this we keep track of if the previous element is same as current element, we skip to the next distinct number, and then apply the same steps as above.

```
class Solution{
    public:
    vector<vector<int> > ans;

    void backtrack(vector<int> a, vector<int> curr, int t, int i){
        // if t is 0, means we formed the group of elements which sum to target,
		// and we push it into our ans.
		if(t==0)
			ans.push_back(curr);

		// but if t<0, means we don't need to check further for this, 
		// as the elements greater than it, won't sum to t.
        if(t<0)    return;

		// to keep track of prev element( -1 is insignificant here.)
        int prev = -1;

        for(; i<a.size(); i++){
			// if prev element is same as current element, we continue.
            if(prev==a[i])  continue;

			// else we append it to current 
            curr.push_back(a[i]);

			// we backtrack for the required element
            backtrack(a, curr, t-a[i], i+1);

			// the other backtrack we use, without using the current element
            curr.pop_back();
            prev = a[i];
        }
    }

    vector<vector<int>> combinationSum2(vector<int> &a, int t){
		// sort the array
        sort(a.begin(), a.end());
        vector<int> temp;temp.clear();
        backtrack(a, temp, t, 0);
        return ans;
    }
};
```

