solutions.content:
A simple way to look at the problem is that for each element in the array, we have two options: **include it or not** in the combination.
Say we're at array index ```i``` with target ```t```. 
*Possibility 1:* If we do include ```array[i]```, the problem becomes "**Find combinations of sum (t - array[i]) in the array starting at i+1**". 
*Possibility 2:* If we do **not** include ```array[i]```, the problem is to "**Find combinations of sum t in the array starting at i+1**".
The only headache left now is to exclude duplicate answers. Duplicate answers exist because we have duplicate elements in the array. 
Say we have *k* ```1```'s. Using the above algorithm, we get *2^k* possiblites. But among them only *(k+1)* possiblities are useful: *0 ... k* of the k ```1```'s are chosen. Thus, we only include the first *n* consecutive ```1```'s. That means **once we decide to uninclude a ```1```, we uninclude all the following ```1```'s**.
Since we consider two possibilities at each index, the execution forms a binary tree with level *n*. The execution time will thus be O(2^n).
```
    public List<List<Integer>> combinationSum2(int[] candidates, int target) {
        List<List<Integer>> res = new LinkedList<List<Integer>>();
        if(candidates == null || candidates.length == 0)
            return res;
        Arrays.sort(candidates);
        combinations(candidates, target, 0, res, new Stack<>());
        return res;
    }

    private void combinations(int[] array, int target, int start, 
                              List<List<Integer>> list, Stack<Integer> stack){
    	if(target == 0)
    		list.add(new ArrayList<Integer>(stack));
        if(target < 0 || start == array.length || target < array[start])
            return;

        //possibility 1: include array[i]
        stack.push(array[start]);
        combinations(array, target-array[start], start+1, list, stack);
        stack.pop();        

        //possibility 2: don't include array[i]
        while(start+1 < array.length && array[start+1]==array[start])
            start++; //exclude duplicates
        combinations(array, target, start+1, list, stack);
    }
```

