solutions.content:
In this post:

these codes may not the fast solution or solution with least lines, but:
**If you understand one question, you can fix all others.**

All of them used the same structure.
--- Bot Up DFS, so we can use memorization to save inmediate results to speed up the algorithm.

**All memorization part are not mandatory** , if you remove these codes, the algorithm still works.

Part 1: Permutations
When order is matter,  we use boolean[] visited to avoid duplicate values.
Part 2: Combination
When order is not necessary,  for (int i = start; i < n; i++)  and dfs(i + 1) to avlid duplicate combination.
Part 3: Set
When the order is not necessary and the size of combination can be different, use a for loop to check the size from 0 to k.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Part one: Permutations
leetcode 46 https://leetcode.com/problems/permutations/
```
class Solution {
    int[] nums;
    boolean[] visited;
    public List<List<Integer>> permute(int[] nums) {
        this.nums = nums;
        this.visited = new boolean[nums.length];
        return permuteDfs(0);
    }

    private List<List<Integer>> permuteDfs(int pos) {

	   if(pos == nums.length) {
            List<List<Integer>> res = new ArrayList<>();
            List<Integer> item = new ArrayList<>();
            res.add(item);
            return res;
        }

        List<List<Integer>> res = new ArrayList<>();

        for (int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
            if(visited[i]) continue;
            visited[i] = true;
            List<List<Integer>> subs = permuteDfs(pos + 1);
            for (List<Integer> sub: subs) {
                List<Integer> item = new ArrayList<>();
                item.add(nums[i]);
                item.addAll(sub);
                res.add(item);
            }
            visited[i] = false;
        }        
        return res;
    }
}
```

