**Approach 1 -- backtracking**
Keep track of a list of existing numbers and residual. When residual drops to 0, add list to answer. Similar to this [thread](https://leetcode.com/problems/combination-sum/discuss/481569/Python3-use-a-stack-to-traverse-the-solution-space-through-backtracking). 

Implementation :
```
class Solution:
    def combinationSum2(self, candidates: List[int], target: int) -> List[List[int]]:
        candidates.sort()

        def fn(i, val): 
            """Populate ans via stack."""
            if val == 0: ans.append(stack.copy())
            elif val > 0: 
                for ii in range(i, len(candidates)): 
                    if i == ii or candidates[ii-1] != candidates[ii]: 
                        stack.append(candidates[ii])
                        fn(ii+1, val - candidates[ii])
                        stack.pop()

        ans, stack = [], []
        fn(0, target)
        return ans
```
Analysis:
Time complexity `O(2^N)`
Space complexity `O(2^N)`

**Approach 2 -- dp**
```
class Solution:
    def combinationSum2(self, candidates: List[int], target: int) -> List[List[int]]:
        candidates.sort()
        dp = [set() for _ in range(target+1)]
        dp[0].add(())
        for x in candidates: 
            for i in reversed(range(target)): 
                if x + i <= target: 
                    for seq in dp[i]: 
                        dp[i+x].add(seq + (x,))
        return dp[-1]
```

Comment: 
Note the similarity to that of [39. Combination Sum](https://leetcode.com/problems/combination-sum/discuss/481569/Python3-A-concise-implementation-of-backtracking-algo).

