solutions.content:
This is kind of  a String-Problem. So the idea first come up to my mind is BackTrack!!
BackTrack is an useful method to traverse all the combinations of string-like brute force. 
Also the solusion is really easy to come up with!

```
 public List<String> wordBreak1(String s, List<String> wordDict) {     
        List<String> res = new ArrayList<>();
        int n=s.length();
        if(n<=0) return res; 
        Set<String> dic = new HashSet<>(wordDict);

        backTrack1(res,"",s,dic,0);

        return res;
    }
    //TLE 
    void backTrack1(List<String> res, String path, String s, Set<String> dic, int idx ){
        if(idx==s.length()){
            res.add(path);
            return;
        }
        for(int i=idx;i<s.length();i++){
            String cur=s.substring(idx,i+1);
            if(dic.contains(cur)){
                if(idx==0)  backTrack1(res, cur,s,dic,i+1);
                else backTrack1(res, path+" "+ cur,s,dic,i+1);
            }
        }   
    }
```
This solusion works correctly! But, in some extremely conditions, it will TLE. 
We know the Time Complexity of BackTrack algorithm is **expotional**( O(N^M) N is the longth of string).

Next step is to improve our solution. 
Lets see the parameters of the method, everytime we use a string to concatenate with other string.
So we can use StringBuilder to replace it. However, only change this, still TLE.

Next, we thought to use some extra memory to improve the running time. It not difficult to come up with the strategy-- **Space exchange Time**!

That is why I thought to use a HashMap to store all the sub-problem results. Each time we get the sub-result only use O(1) time.  Here is the code!

```
  public List<String> wordBreak(String s, List<String> wordDict) {

        List<String> res = new ArrayList<>();
        int n=s.length();
		//This is the conner case
        if(n<=0) return res;

		//change the List to the Set, becasue we always want to check with it.
        Set<String> dic = new HashSet<>(wordDict);

        res =backTrack(s,dic);

        return res;
    }

    //Using hashMap to store the sub-problem results
    HashMap<String,List<String>> map = new HashMap<>();

    List<String> backTrack(String s, Set<String> dic){

        List<String> res  = new ArrayList<>();
		//this is the conner case
        if(s.length()<=0){
            res.add("");
            return res;
        }

        for(int i=0;i<s.length();i++){
			//we get cur split string
            String cur=s.substring(0,i+1);

            if(dic.contains(cur)){  

                String next=s.substring(i+1);
                List<String> subans =new ArrayList<>();
				//here our map used
                if(map.containsKey(next)){
                    subans=map.get(next);
                }else{
                    subans = backTrack(next,dic);
                } 
				//combine the total answer
                for(String str:subans){            
                    if(str.equals("")) res.add(cur);
                    else res.add(cur+" "+str);
                }
            }
        }
		//add this level result to the map
        map.put(s,res);
        return res;  
   }
```
