We can take advantage of the fact that our given input input grid is sorted. So if we are at a particular element we are guranteed that all the element to it's right and to it's bottom will be larger that the current element.
And we also know that all the element to it's left and to it's top will be less than the current element;

So this potentially allow us to eliminte :
	Either all the element below and to the right if our target is less that the current elemet `target < grid[i][j]`
	Or we can eliminate all the elements to the left and top if our target is greater that the current     element `target > grid[i][j]`

