solutions.content:
The Brute Force solution takes time O(m * n).

To optimize,  let's observe how we can take advantage of the matrix's property.
```
1. if there is only one row, if curDigit 
                >  target, we check digits to its left
                <  target, we check digits to its right
2. if there is only one col, if curDigit 
                >  target, we check digits on its top
                <  target, we check digits on its bottom
3. if a curDigit is at the cross of a row and a col,
	    if curDigit 
                >  target, we check digits to its left AND on its top
                <  target, we check digits to its right AND on its bottom

        BUT if we traverse the matrix from the bottom-left corner, then we only have to move top / right, since other digits have been invalidated already, that is,
	    if curDigit
                >  target, we check digits to its top
                <  target, we check digits on its right

        OR if we traverse the matrix from the top-right corner, then we only have to move bottom / left, since other digits have been invalidated already, that is,
	    if curDigit
                >  target, we check digits to its left
                <  target, we check digits on its bottom
```
This approach takes time O(m + n).

****
**Bottom-left**
```
class Solution {
    public boolean searchMatrix(int[][] matrix, int target) { 
