<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
This is a Java code for the "Search a 2D Matrix II" problem, where given an m x n matrix sorted in non-decreasing order, we need to check if a given integer target is present in the matrix
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
The approach used in this code is to start from the bottom left corner of the matrix and compare the target with the element at this position. If the target is smaller, we move one row up; if it is larger, we move one column right; and if it is equal, we return true. We repeat this process until we find the target or reach the top right corner of the matrix.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(m+n), since we traverse at most m rows and n columns of the matrix. 

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(1), since we use only a constant amount of extra space.

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public boolean searchMatrix(int[][] matrix, int target) {
        int m=matrix.length-1;
        int n=matrix[0].length-1;
        int i=m;
        int j=0;
        while(i>=0 && j<=n)
        {
            if(target < matrix[i][j])
            {
                i--;
            }
            else if(target > matrix[i][j])
            {
                j++;
            }
            else
            {
                return true;
            }
        }
        return false;
    }

}
```

