solutions.content:
Hey everyone,
So, when I first saw this problem, it was obvious that it should be something like Binary Search or some kind of traversal of the matrix (matrix, sorted, you know..), but how to implement it, thats the real trick. 

The brute force will work (although it will be TLE), so I started by thinking of BS of each row and column (vertical / horizontal) but again, time complexity will be high, and then I finally got the trick.

We were able to perform BS on our matrix, due to the fact its sorted, and that fact - we need to use when we iterating 2D matrix. So I played a little with the matrix in my iPad with 2D matrix in the size of `5x5` and `target=8`.

#### So, the steps were: 

1. If I will start from bottom to up, with initiate state of `row = 4, col = 0`, I will know for sure that the `target` is bigger or lower than the current element, and if it equal to, return `True` (otherwise, `False`).
2. In each step I check, if the `first element` (and later on, the the `col` element) of row is bigger/lower than the `target`.
2.1. If `matrix[row][col]` is bigger, decrease `row`.
The target will probably be in lower row index.
2.2. If `matrix[row][col]` is lower, increase `col`.
The target will probably be in higher column index.
3. If none was found (loop constraints), so it will return `False`.
Otherwise the `matrix[row][col]` is equal to the target and return `True`.
4. With that matrix traversal, we increasing/decreasing the row/col index due to the constraints of the matrix and we will get O(n) + O(m) operations O(n+m), each operations is O(1) and we are not using additional space, so space complexity will be O(1).

In the image below, you can see how it possible to ignore all the unrelevant elements in the matrix.

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/7c93da94-a54c-42b4-a5a1-98885e020ab8_1658678638.0849197.png)

#### The Solution

```
class Solution {
    public boolean searchMatrix(int[][] array, int target) {
        int row = array.length - 1;
        int col = 0;

        // o(n + m) operations + o(1) space
        while(row >= 0 && col < array[0].length) {
            int element = array[row][col];
            if(element > target) {
                row--;
            } else if(element < target) {
                col++;
            } else {
                return true;
            }
        }

        return false;
    }
}
```

Hope it was helpful to you all!

