Runtime is 6 ms.
I know this can be improved a little bit, but it should be sufficient from Interview point of view. Technically, this solution is equivalent to solving 3 different problems. Look at the comments for understanding.

I think worst case could happen when all the elements in the row or column for the given indexes are duplicates, which will cause the **binary search** to run for each element in the corresponding row or column. This might make the current solution O(m + n), but I think, this can also be avoided by doing some extra checks on start and end indexes.
```
class Solution {
    public boolean searchMatrix(int[][] matrix, int target) {
        if (matrix == null) {
            return false;
        }

        int m = matrix.length;
        if (m == 0) {
            return false;
        }

        int n = matrix[0].length;

        int row = 0;
        int col = n-1;
        // Start from Top right entry in the matrix.
        // If target is less than the entry, we do binary search on the row.
        // Else, we do binary search on the column
        while (row < m && col >= 0) {
		    // Target is found
            if (matrix[row][col] == target) {
                return true;
            }

            if (matrix[row][col] > target) {
				// If target is less than the current item, we do a binary search on the current row to find the appropriate column
                col = searchRow(matrix, row, col-1, target);
            } else {
				// If target is greater than the current item, we do a binary search on the current column to find the appropriate row
                row = searchCol(matrix, col, row+1, target);
            }
        }

        return false;
    }

    // Binary search on the row and return index of column for the possible entry
    // Technically, this is finding the first index of repeated target element in a sorted array, if the target exists.
    // Otherwise, it is just returning the index where target should have been in that particular row.
    private int searchRow(int[][] matrix, int rowIdx, int colEndIdx, int target) {
        int mid;
        int start = 0;
        int end = colEndIdx;

        while (start < end) {
            mid = start + ((end-start)/2);

            if (matrix[rowIdx][mid] >= target) {
                end = mid;
            } else {
                start = mid + 1;
            }
        }

        return end;
    }

    // Binary search on the column and return index of row for the possible entry
    // Technically, this is finding the last index of repeated target element in a sorted array, if the target exists.
    // Otherwise, it is just returning the index where target should have been in that particular column.
    private int searchCol(int[][] matrix, int colIdx, int rowStartIdx, int target) {
        int mid;
        int start = rowStartIdx;
        int end = matrix.length;

        while (start < end) {
            mid = start + ((end-start)/2);

            if (matrix[mid][colIdx] >= target) {
                end = mid;
            } else {
                start = mid + 1;
            }
        }

        return end;
    }
}
```

