# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
I struggled a long time with this problem until I got it. Wouldn't have solved it during a 1hr interview but I learned some along the way.

Eventually what I realized is that
* all numbers in 1..n starting with 1 come before 2, those starting with 2 come before 3, etc.
* all numbers starting with 10 come before 11, and so on
* for a prefix such as 30, 30 comes before 30x, which comes before 30xy, etc.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

Suppose we had a function `startingWith(prefix, n)`that returned the number of values in 1..n that start with a given prefix. Then
* `startingWith(1, n)` tells us if the result starts with 1:
  * if the result is `<= k` then the result starts with 1
  * if the result is `> k` then the result starts with 2 or more

Then we can do the same thing with `startingWith(2, n)`. If the number starting with 1 and 2 are fewer than k, the result must start with 3 or more. Otherwise the result starts with 2.

So I rewrote this loop as follows:
* we have a counter `rem` that tells us the number of values in the lexically ordered sequence we have left to go
* and a current `prefix`; the result is either `prefix` itself or starts wth prefix

We start with the lowest prefix: 1.

If the number of values left to go is exactly 1, the answer is the current prefix: it comes before `<prefix>0`, `<prefix>00`, etc.

If the number of values left to go is MORE than the number starting with the current prefix, we advance to the next prefix and subtract the number of values we just skipped over.

Otherwise the value starts with something in `<prefix>0`, `<prefix>9`. So we move on to `<prefix>0` and decrement `rem` (because we advance past `<prefix>` itself).

# Counting the number of values in 1..n starting with prefix

After struggling a bit here as well I figured out the following: for a given prefix there are the following numbers that may be $\leq n$:
* `<prefix>` itself
* `<prefix>0` to `<prefix>9`
* `<prefix>00` to `<prefix>99`

The next prefix is `<prefix+1>`, so in the loop I made (`numStartingWith`) we increment count by 1 for `<prefix>`, then by up to 10 for `<prefix>0 .. <prefix>9`, then by up to 100, etc. The loop stops when the `<prefix>00...0` is larger than $n$ so there can't be any more numbers starting with `prefix` left to add.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(\log(n)^2)$$

We spend at most 9 iterations to find out what the first digit of the result is. Then we spend at most 10 iteratiosn to find out what the next digit is.

The number of digits in the result is the number of digits in $n$, i.e. $\log(n)$ digits.

In each of those calls, we have an $O(\log(n))$ loop to find the number of values starting with the current prefix.

- Space complexity: $$O(1)$$, we just have a couple of counters

# Code
```
class Solution {
    /** Returns the number of integers in 1..n with the given lexical prefix */
    int numStartingWith(int prefix, int n) {

        int count = 0;
        long lo = prefix; // [lo, hi) with current number of digits
        long hi = prefix+1;
        while (lo <= n) {
            count += min(hi-lo, n-lo+1);
            lo *= 10;
            hi *= 10;
        }
        printf("numStartingWith(%i, %i) == %i\n", prefix, n, count);
        return count;
    }

public:
    int findKthNumber(int n, int k) {
        // suppose we know the number of integers <= n that start with a prefix
        //   if it's fewer than k, we move on to the next prefix and decrement some remaining counter `rem`
        //   if it's more than `rem`, e.g. maybe there are more numbers starting with 20 ...
        //   

        // e.g.  n = 127 and k = 40, rem = 40
        //   num starting with 1 is 32 (100..127, 10..12, 1). 32 < 40 so we move on to 2-something, and rem = 8
        //   num starting with 2 is 11, 11 >= 8 so the result lexically starts with 2
        //       // we've narrowed it down to 2, 2x, 2xy, 2xyz, etc.
        //       rem > 1 so we rule out 2 itself
        //       prefix = 20 and rem = 7
        //         num starting with 20 is 1, so move on to next prefix 21
        //         num starting with 21 is 1,

        int prefix = 1; // current prefix
        int rem = k; // number to go
        while (true) {
            if (rem == 1) return prefix; 
            int count = numStartingWith(prefix, n);
            if (count < rem) {
                ++prefix; // can skip past all `count` numbers <= n starting with this prefix
                rem -= count;
            } else {
                // prefix => <prefix>0, e.g. more than `rem` nums start with <30>, so we skip past 30 and move on to 300
                --rem;
                prefix *= 10;
            }
        }
        return prefix;
    }
};
```

