**Attacking the problem**
You start with B.S. as the question is tagged as B.S. and then think that the array is sorted so B.S. it is.
**Stuck!! How do I know if I go left or right from the middle :(**
Okay jokes apart this is a really good problem on B.S. and let us carefully analyse what we are given.
The array is sorted and as only one unique element and other elements exist as pairs. 
DIY take few example arrays and write the indices above all the elements. 
**Observe** 
Got something?
No?
**Observe again and look at the indices of pairs on the left of the unique element and on the right of the unique element**

We see that for every case on the left of the unique element the pairs exist as (even,odd), (even,odd),......(even)
where singular (even) is the index of the unique element. 
(It can be easily concluded that the index of the unique element will always be even.)
After the unique element the pairs on the right exist as (odd,even),(odd,even),........
So are we still stuck on where to go, left or right? 
By seeing this pattern we have found two distinct search spaces and we can move towards the unique element by checking in which search space we are in.
If we are in the left search space we go right.
If we are in the right search space we go left.
I leave the code for your reference below. 

```
int singleNonDuplicate(vector<int>& nums) {
        if(nums.size()==1)
            return nums[0];
        int l = 0,r=nums.size()-1;
        while(l<=r){
            int m = l + (r-l)/2;
            if(m%2){
				// (even odd) i.e. we are on the left side of unique element--> go right
                if(nums[m-1]==nums[m])
                    l = m+1;
				// (even odd) pair violated, happens on the right side of unique element--> go left
                else{
                    r = m-1;
                }
            }else{
				// (even odd) i.e. we are on the left side of unique element--> go right
                if(nums[m]==nums[m+1]){
                    l = m+1;
				// (even odd) pair violated, happens on the right side of unique element--> go left
                }else{
                    r = m-1;
                }
            }
        }
        return nums[l];
    }
