solutions.content:
**Intuition:**
Sorted array!
That suggests we can use binary search.
Then I will use classical binary search template: [low_index, high_index)
The middle value are highlighted in red color.

There is some observation about potential place for the unique item: it must be in an even-indexed position
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/codedayday/image_1589322173.png)

Note, for original middle value of ex3 and ex4, the middle indices need to be decreased by 1 and converted in ex3’, and ex4’ respectively. The unique number, highlighted in green, must occupied an even-index position.

One more fun knowledge about i-th index in zero-index space is that i means there are i items have smaller indices then current i-th item:
For example,
nums[i]
means there are i items are in the left of nums[i].
What does it mean to this question?
Okay, if some index, say, mid,  is even, then it means there are even number of items in the left of the mid.

```
class Solution {//BEST: binary search
public://Time/Space: O(logN); O(1)
    int singleNonDuplicate(vector<int>& nums) {
        const int n = nums.size();
        int lo = 0, hi = n;
        if(n==1) return nums[0];
        while(lo<hi){
            int mid = lo + (hi - lo) / 2;
            if(mid%2 == 1) mid--; //  if mid%2 == 1; then at least two items are there.
            if(nums[mid] == nums[mid+1]) // left and current duet are all alright
                lo = mid +2;  // then move right by two positions.
            else hi = mid;  // note, mid is even index, a potential home for unique number
        }
        return nums[lo];
    }
};


```

