solutions.content:
This is a basic binary search, with some modifications that follow naturally.

First: In order to determine if you've landed on the correct element, then you need to compare the current value with the previous and the next element. If you're on the correct element, then all three elements are different.

So, change #1 looks something like this:
```
int prevVal = nums[mid - 1];
int nextVal = nums[mid + 1];
if (midVal != prevVal && midVal != nextVal) {
  return midVal;
}
```

This now leads to the second modification of binary search. Since we need to check the next value and the previous value,
there's new bounds checking we need to do  - if the target index is the beginning or the end of the array.

For the ends of the array, if the midpoint has reached that point, then (at best) the possible indices are [0, 1] if it's the start or [n - 2, n - 1] for the end. With a little bit of thought, we realize that the only valid case if the midpoint gets to this point is the very last item.
Let's consider the two possible cases:
[0, 1, 1, ....]
[1, 1, 2, 3, 3, ...]
It's not possible for the target index to be 1, because for that to happen the previous item would have to be duplicated. However there's no place for the matching pair to go. The same logic follows for the end.

That leads to this bit of code:
```
if (mid == 0 || mid == numsSize - 1) {
  return nums[mid];
}
```

And now the very last thing to do is to figure out which direction to go. Here's the part where you have to sit and think about it for a bit and come up with the trick. The trick is that before the singleton, each pair starts at an even index. E.g. indices 0, 2, 4, 6, 8, ... all contain the first number of a pair. Then there's a singleton, which is on an even index. Then there are more pairs afterwards. These pairs after the singleton are out-of-phase. They start on an odd index. Let's look at an example:
```
indices: [0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8]
values:  [2, 2, 3, 3, 6, 7, 7, 8, 8]
```
Note how the pair of 2's starts at index 0, the pair of 3's starts at index 2. Then we hit the unique number.
The 7's start at index 5.

Now we have the insight to figure out whether to search high or low for the unique number.

```
const bool isPair = midVal == nextVal;
if ((mid % 2 == 0) ^ isPair) {
	high = mid;
} else {
	low = mid + 1;
}
```
The XOR is just a shorthand way of writing `(if mid %2 == 0 && !isPair || mid % 2 != 0 && isPair)`

Put everything together and you get a solution like this.
```
int singleNonDuplicate(int* nums, int numsSize){
    int low = 0;
    int high = numsSize;
    while (low < high) {
        const int mid = low + (high - low) / 2;
        const int midVal = nums[mid];
        if (mid == 0 || mid == numsSize - 1) {
          return midVal;
        }

        int prevVal = nums[mid - 1];
        int nextVal = nums[mid + 1];
        if (midVal != prevVal && midVal != nextVal) {
            return midVal;
        }

        bool isPair = midVal == nextVal;

        if ((mid % 2 == 0) ^ isPair) {
            high = mid;
        } else {
            low = mid + 1;
        }
    }
    return -1;
}
```

